					<div id="post_message_1831857">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							So, I've mentioned this a few times in the new releases threads, but PC game releases are becoming harder and harder to keep track of. With the explosion of &quot;indie gaming&quot; and no reliance on physical items to stock at retail, quality PC games often do not have official release dates. A large amount become available even before they are technically finished.<br />
<br />
It is for this reason that I thought we could try an experiment with this thread. I can't keep up with all the new releases on Steam, especially with Early Access, but I know several of you prefer PC games to the console stuff I usually end up talking about in new release threads. So, if anyone stumbles upon something that is particularly cool, you can post about it in here.<br />
<br />
I am not sure if this thread is needed or will show much use, but figured we could give it a shot anyway. I will still talk about games with solid release dates in the monthly threads as usual, but so much falls through the cracks and it's impossible to keep up with it all. <br />
<br />
I know in the past some of you have both recommended things in the monthly release threads, or made entirely new threads for a game. The latter is arguably the most effective, but if you like, you can post stuff here too. <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
As a bit of an aside, I saw someone on another forum mention that Steam is practically the new Newgrounds these days. They are so, so right. For anyone who doesn't know, Newgrounds was a website that users could post games and animations they created with flash to share with others. It was a breeding ground of both creativity and garbage. Every now and then you would find something that was particularly amazing (for a flash game), and it of course was free.<br />
<br />
This recent trend of indie game bandwagon jumping is a little ridiculous to me as a result. There is a lot of good stuff being made that wasn't being made before, but there are a lot of people making simple things that in another life would have been a free diversion that is now being sold in a storefront, and clogging up the listings making it that much harder to separate the wheat from the chaff.<br />
<br />
Anyway, mini rant over, just thought it was an interesting observation.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
				<!-- edit note -->
				<blockquote class="postcontent lastedited">
