				<img src="image.php?s=c7bf4f3981dfc4446625a29fe82c408f&amp;u=7104&amp;dateline=1279754648" alt="Wool's Avatar" title="Wool's Avatar" />
			</a>
			 
			
				<hr />
				<dl class="userinfo_extra">
					<dt>Join Date</dt> <dd>Sep 2004</dd>
					
					
					<dt>Posts</dt> <dd>12,976</dd>	
					
				</dl>
				
				
				<div class="imlinks">
					    
				</div>
			
		</div>
		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: The Recommend a PC Game Thread
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1837572">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							I got The Talos Principle during the Steam Sale, and thought it was quite good. It's worth recommending, and wasn't a major hyped release so is easy to overlook. I think it probably qualifies as a sleeper hit, as it came out of nowhere and impressed a lot of PC gamers.<br />
<br />
So what is it? The Talos Principle is a first person puzzle game of a similar style to Portal. You are presented with segmented levels and given unique tools to work your way through them. I don't think the puzzles are as clever as the ones in Portal, but they do get a good bit harder and have more variety. <br />
<br />
While it is a great puzzle game, what I most enjoyed about it was probably the story. It does not have the wit or the charm of Portal, and it definitely doesn't have the same production values. If you just play the game, you will get almost no story out of it and be one of those sad, confused people who complain about not understanding the ending when you are done. The Talos Principle is one of those few games where the story justifies listening to the audio diaries and reading all the text files (don't worry they are easy to find).<br />
<br />
So in this game you play as a robot. You wake up and are told by the voice of God that if you undertake trials you will be granted eternal life. Along the way you will find QR codes that act as messages from others that came before you. There are weird glitches in the world around you, and computer terminals that you can log into for bits and pieces of information. Some of these terminals are interactive in interesting ways. It's up to you to decide if you care about the mystery or if you should just do as you are told.<br />
<br />
Ever want to argue with a grouchy computer about whether or not you actually exist, and then have it get angsty with you when you don't agree with it? This game is for you. The plot of the game relies very heavily on philosophy and science fiction. I thought it was very intelligent and exactly the sort of thing some of you might find interesting. It's actually fairly moving as well, considering there really is no drama at play here, simply a presentation of ideas.<br />
<br />
Highly recommended. Key words: puzzles, philosophy, science fiction.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
