		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: The Recommend a PC Game Thread
				</h2>
				

						
						
							
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1846693">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							I'm going to talk about two of the games I got in the Steam sale. <br />
<br />
First is Invisible, Inc. I'm not going to go into too much detail on this. The people who made Mark of the Ninja made a turn based stealth game. Imagine X-Com where combat is not the focus, and you instead have to infiltrate high tech corporations and steal their stuff. It also does the &quot;limited time&quot; thing, but is much more strict so you don't have the same luxury to maximize all your agents for the final confrontation. It's shorter, and is similar to roguelikes in that it is meant to be replayed, with you unlocking new agents each playthrough.<br />
<br />

<iframe class="restrain" title="YouTube video player" width="640" height="390" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/WZ8b_J7DS64?wmode=opaque" frameborder="0"  allowfullscreen webkitallowfullscreen  mozallowfullscreen ></iframe>
<br />
<br />
<br />
Second is Rogue Galaxy. I was in the mood for a space ship game, but didn't want to commit to a complicated sim. The sell I've seen people using for this game is &quot;Freelancer + Firefly, with Black Flag combat&quot;. I'll explain the reasons for comparison below. I also want to point out right now that it was made by only two people.<br />
<br />
Firefly - The aesthetic and general style of Rebel Galaxy utilizes the trope in which space (or at least the fringe regions of space) is a frontier full of rednecks, space cowboys, and space truckers. The law is full of stuffed shirts that do nothing but tell you what you can or cannot trade. The music itself is very folk bluesy and country rocky. I don't know the specific genre. Though I will also say that if you don't like it, the game has a feature in which you not only import your own songs, but can designate at what point they play (station outfitting, travel, combat, etc).<br />
<br />
Freelancer - The solar systems you access are procedurally generated, and aside from following the main story quest, you are given the freedom to choose between fighting pirates, running trade routes, mining, or being a pirate yourself. Space stations, when spawned, are assigned a &quot;government&quot; and an &quot;economy&quot; rating that determines what they buy or sell. There are also random station events (war, famine, invasion, blockade) that change the prices further and can be used to your advantage. <br />
<br />
Black Flag - Referring to the 4th Assassin's Creed game, in which you had a naval combat mode emphasizing lining up for broadside attacks. The combat is similar in Rebel Galaxy. You have multiple classes of ship to choose from, but they emphasize capital ships rather than fighters like in most sims. You have multiple turret types and hardpoints to select, but these can be automated. You also have secondary systems and primary guns, which tend to be on the side of the ship. You try to manuever and get shots in, while also trying to avoid too much damage to your shields, which is location based (front, each side, rear).<br />
<br />
<br />
I enjoyed it, it does have a few flaws though. Content wise, it's a little shallow. You have the option to do trading, or mining, or what have you, but these are just side activities to the combat. This isn't a game where you can be a space trader and nothing else. It's more a way to make extra money to climb up the grind ladder than a central gameplay focus. In fact, the high level trading missions might be more obnoxious than the high level combat missions, as you tend to be ambushed continually by huge fleets of ships with engine jammers.<br />
<br />
The game also sort of suffers somewhat from stat inflation. The game determines success based on the level of your equipment, rather than the ship itself. What this means is that each new solar system you go to has a jump in difficulty because the stats of ships change. Shield and hull in particular will often double when you upgrade to the next tier of equipment. This makes the game really grindy, as you perform repetitive missions or trade routes to get enough money to just keep doing the same thing you were already doing. The jump isn't insurmountable mind you, but it may feel like a little more effort than is worthwhile to try and fight things you aren't equipped for.<br />
<br />
Part of the reason for this is because there are many classes of ships, and they wanted you to be able to choose which one you liked, rather than feel you had to have the biggest and best. The smaller class of ship you are using, the faster you are. The larger the ship you are using, the more firepower you have. Shields and hull will stay the same.<br />
<br />
<br />

<iframe class="restrain" title="YouTube video player" width="640" height="390" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/HMZPVgycrAE?wmode=opaque" frameborder="0"  allowfullscreen webkitallowfullscreen  mozallowfullscreen ></iframe>

						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
